div.font: Define infrastructure as code with Terraform. Deploy with GitHub Actions

div.style: font-size: 12px;
font-size: 12px;
div.font: Two AWS accounts needed for prod/non-prod.
div.span: Production account should trust the non-prod account and a have a role that (certain) developers can assume after they sign in to the non-prod account.

div.style: font-size: 12px;
font-size: 12px;
font-size: 12px;

li.font: No Apache httpd servers, AWS ALBs instead
No VNS3 server - primarily using Systems Manager Session Manager with SSH bastion as fallback

li.span: No Jenkins or OpsWorks - deploy changes with GitHub Actions/Terraform/CodeDeploy instead

li.font: Run the CPM on Fargate (managed ECS) instead of EC2
Run Keycloak on Fargate, use S3 for cluster management instead of UDP multicast/Transit Gateway
Run the “internal” and “fo-to-pdf” apps on Fargate instead of sharing the Delta EC2 instances
Actually use the autoscaling groups where we can (Digital Space only uses them for auto-heal)
Deploy MarkLogic using their template for a managed cluster: https://docs.marklogic.com/guide/ec2/CloudFormation
Use AWS Directory Service for the AD domain controllers instead of managing the instances directly. Will replicate the current CA setup for LDAPS (single-tier)
Replacing Squid server with AWS Network Firewall, with filtering per-subnet
Replacing the FTP server with S3 (data export to DAP)
CloudWatch for logs and monitoring, with developers having access to view logs and dashboards
Secrets Manager will be used for storing secrets rather than including them in deployment artefacts

div.style: font-size: 12px;
font-size: 12px;

ul.li: Each application (Delta website, API, Keycloak, CPM, Jasper Reports) has its own CloudFront distribution, all of them are protected by AWS WAF
We use VPC Endpoints to securely send requests to AWS services from our VPC

li.span: Jaspersoft servers will end up similar to the current setup, but managed through Terraform. The Jaspersoft server is customised and uses an old version, with the current version not being compatible with Delta. We've patched what we can and will IP restrict it to improve security.
CPM, the API and Keycloak are all IP restricted to the same list as the current production environment (using AWS WAF)
The public ALBs will only accept requests from our CloudFront distributions, based on a key in a header
